<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-383-612  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 383 612.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  April 12 1990 n1209 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Changes that spell death to the middle manager.(results of asurvey of senior executives)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mitchell, Amanda.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A recent survey by management consultancy Arthur D. Little leadsto the conclusion that the 1990s will see middle level managementpositions eliminated by information-based technology.andP;  The survey,conducted of 112 senior executives of multinational corporations,paints a much different vision of the future of corporations thanthat predicted by social experts during the 1970s and 1980s, whenit was thought that lower level positions, such as secretarial andclerical jobs, would be made redundant by increased use ofinformation technology.andP;  The information-based organization, aconcept of management scientist Peter Drucker, is a flatterorganization, with significantly fewer levels of management.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Arthur D. Little Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Management StyleSurveyTrendsOrganization Structure.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>